{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78185c9e-f55a-4164-9099-9f15c7c844d8","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Action | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate the app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e331de4d-05bf-4bd5-94b1-20b819472af3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":408},"id":"e24ac349-c1b7-4bd7-b2ee-104120ad3fcd","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:58.235Z","parentId":"401311e3-6ede-4b58-bd45-f345d788a37d"}
